  "prompt": "What is the difference between FRS, PRD, TRD, SRS, MRD, BRD?",
  "response": "Each of these acronyms refers to a different type of document used in software development and product management. Here\u2019s a brief overview of each:\n\n1. **FRS (Functional Requirements Specification)**:\n   - **Purpose**: Defines the functionality that the system must have. It specifies what the system should do.\n   - **Contents**: Detailed use cases, user interactions, and the specific behaviors of the system.\n\n2. **PRD (Product Requirements Document)**:\n   - **Purpose**: Describes the product\u2019s purpose, features, functionality, layout, and behavior.\n   - **Contents**: Market needs, target audience, product vision, features, requirements, and specifications. It often includes both functional and non-functional requirements.\n\n3. **TRD (Technical Requirements Document)**:\n   - **Purpose**: Outlines the technical aspects of the system, including technological solutions, architectures, constraints, and standards.\n   - **Contents**: System architecture, technology stack, integration requirements, scalability, performance considerations, and technical specifications.\n\n4. **SRS (Software Requirements Specification)**:\n   - **Purpose**: Provides a comprehensive description of the intended software product.\n   - **Contents**: Detailed functional and non-functional requirements, use cases, data models, system interfaces, and acceptance criteria. Essentially, it encompasses both FRS and technical aspects required for software development.\n\n5. **MRD (Marketing Requirements Document)**:\n   - **Purpose**: Defines the market requirements and business case for a product.\n   - **Contents**: Market analysis, competitive landscape, customer needs, key product features, strategic alignment, and marketing strategy.\n\n6. **BRD (Business Requirements Document)**:\n   - **Purpose**: Captures the business needs and objectives to be addressed by the proposed solution.\n   - **Contents**: Business goals, objectives, stakeholder needs, business rules, and high-level requirements that align with the organization's strategy.\n\n### Key Differences:\n\n- **FRS vs. SRS**: FRS focuses solely on functional requirements, while SRS includes both functional and non-functional requirements and can be considered more comprehensive.\n- **PRD vs. BRD**: PRD is product-centric and includes detailed features and functionality, while BRD is business-centric and focuses on business objectives and high-level requirements.\n- **TRD vs. FRS**: TRD concentrates on the technical details and constraints, whereas FRS is focused on functional requirements from a user and system perspective.\n- **MRD**: Covers market-specific needs and competitive analysis, often used to justify the need for a product in a specific market.\n\nUnderstanding these documents is crucial for successful product development as they each serve distinct purposes in the overall process.",
